        <h2>From ATAC to Praxis: Four Years of Transformation</h2>
        <p>In August 2020, five directly impacted Arizonans filed corporate papers to create Arizonans for Transparency and Accountability in Corrections (ATAC). Co-founder John Fabricius had just spent 15 years across nine ADCRR complexes and watched his older brother die of an overdose after being denied treatment. Jessica Johnson brought eight years of experience from Perryville Prison. J Alexandria Hunt-Garcia contributed policy expertise and digital organizing skill. With no funding, no political connections, and no template to follow in Arizona, they began filing public records requests, building a volunteer network, and tracking every death, assault, and policy failure.</p>
        <p>For four years, ATAC operated as a volunteer-powered machine. We published quarterly "Death in Custody" reports that legislators couldn't ignore. We organized families who hadn't heard from loved ones during lockdowns. We partnered with journalism students to analyze ADCRR's own data, revealing systemic medical neglect. By 2023, ATAC had become a respected—if feared—voice at the Capitol, known for showing up prepared, speaking truth, and never backing down. Federal litigation (Jensen v. Shinn) confirmed ADCRR's constitutional violations, validating our work.</p>
        <p>The 2025 legislative session changed everything. After years of exposing retaliation against incarcerated whistleblowers and medical neglect that cost lives, bipartisan momentum shifted. Senate Bill 1507 created the Office of Independent Correctional Ombudsman, mandating unannounced inspections, subpoena power, and a citizen board with mandatory seats for directly impacted individuals. When Governor Katie Hobbs signed it into law, ATAC's founders knew their original mission was complete—and it was time to expand.</p>
